The economy of Gabon is characterized by its substantial ties to [France](/France), significant foreign direct investment, a reliance on a skilled foreign workforce, and a concerning decline in its agricultural sector. Despite possessing a per capita income that, on paper, is four times that of many other African nations, its deep-seated dependence on the resource extraction industry has proven insufficient to lift a large segment of the population out of poverty. This economic structure, while generating wealth, has not effectively disseminated it, leaving a considerable portion of the population in conditions of [extreme poverty](/Extreme_poverty).

The nation operates under a [free market economy](/Free_markets), though some sources argue for a [mixed economic system](/Mixed_economy). This classification highlights the dominant role of oil revenue, alongside a system where centralized economic planning and government oversight may not always be robust.

